{{also|niger|Níger}}
==English==

===Etymology===
Commonly linked by [[folk etymology]] to {{cog|la|niger||black}}, which likely influenced the modern spelling.

Some sources give the term to {{der|en|tmh|-}} roots, deriving it from a claimed {{m|tmh||gher n-gheren}} or {{m|tmh||egereou n-igereouen|t=river of rivers}}.<ref name=meek1960>C. K. Meek, [http://www.jstor.org/stable/179702 The Niger and the Classics: The History of a Name]. The Journal of African History. Vol. 1, No. 1 (1960), pp. 1-17</ref><ref>{{R:Etymonline}}</ref>

Older sources derive ''Niger'', via a series of mistranslations and geographic misplacements by Greek, Roman and Arab geographers, from Ptolemy's descriptions of the [[wadi]] Gir (in modern Algeria) and the "Lower Gir" (or "Ni-Gir") to the south.<ref>compare: ''The Penny Cyclopædia of the Society for the Diffusion of useful Knowledge'', vol. 16 (Murillo—Organ), 1840, ''NIGER, or rather NIGIR''</ref>

